ived \u03b1-ketoglutarate from the Hydrothermal environment at the pyrrhotite-catalyzed transamination. This is arguably the most prebiotically plausible route, combining two well-established paradigms. The glycine Strecker synthesis (rxn_017) is one of the most robust reactions in prebiotic chemistry. The transamination on pyrrhotite (rxn_009) is directly supported by Menor-Salv\u00e1n et al. (2013). Note: this pathway implicitly requires the full rTCA chain to produce \u03b1-ketoglutarate, so the 5 steps listed may undercount the total.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Clarify that the 5-step count includes either the rTCA subpath or references it explicitly\", \"The glyoxylate byproduct (mol_024) from rxn_009 could be recycled\u2014consider showing this\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_014\": 0.40,\n                \"rxn_016\": 0.80\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.48,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.50,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.60,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.55,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.50,\n            \"feedback\": \"Shares the same fatal flaw as P2: rxn_014 is stoichiometrically and mechanistically impossible as written. The cyanamide-assisted hydrolysis (rxn_016) is well-supported by Parker et al. (2014) and adds a genuine improvement over simple hydrolysis. However, the pathway cannot be approved due to the broken first step.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Fix rxn_014 as described for P2\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_010\": 0.75,\n                \"rxn_011\": 0.70,\n                \"rxn_012\": 0.8