back\": \"An efficient 4-step cyanosulfidic pathway aligned with Sutherland's systems chemistry framework. HCN tetramerization to DAMN is well-established. The fragmentation of DAMN to acrylonitrile (rxn_013) is somewhat simplified\u2014Sutherland's actual chemistry involves UV-driven photoredox with Cu catalysis, and the specific product from DAMN fragmentation should be clarified. rxn_017 (acrylonitrile + HCN + NH3 \u2192 2-aminopentanedinitrile) compresses hydrocyanation and amination into one step. The final hydrolysis is straightforward but slow without catalysis.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_017\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Specify UV irradiation and Cu photoredox for rxn_013\", \"Clarify the mechanism of rxn_017: sequential HCN addition then amination?\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_012\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_013\": 0.70,\n                \"rxn_017\": 0.70,\n                \"rxn_019\": 0.85\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.80,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n            \"feedback\": \"Identical to P4 but with cyanamide-assisted hydrolysis (rxn_019), which is directly supported by Parker et al. (2014) reanalysis of Miller's 1958 experiments. The cyanamide acts as a condensing agent that enhances amino acid yields and facilitates the nitrile-to-acid conversion. This is one of the strongest literature-supported pathways in the network. The Surface\u2192Biochemical environmental flow is appropriate for cyanosulfidic chemistry feeding into aqueous hydrolysis pools.\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_017\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Mention Cu photoredox cycling for rxn_013\", \"Consider adding phosphate buffer as co-catalyst per Sutherland's protocols\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_003\": 0.70,\n                \"rxn_014\": 0.65,\n                \"rxn_015\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_016\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_018\": 0.80\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.79,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.85,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.90,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.85,\n            \"feedback\": \"Excellent environmental flow: Hydrothermal (formaldehyde) \u2192 Surface (acrolein, Strecker) \u2192 Biochemical (hydrolysis). The Strecker synthesis via acrolein is strongly supported by literature as a primary route to glutamate precursors. rxn_015 (Michael addition of HCN to acrolein) and rxn_016 (Strecker on 3-cyanopropanal) are both textbook chemistry with high plausibility. Weaknesses: rxn_003 (CO2 \u2192 formaldehyde via FTT) is thermodynamically challenging, and rxn_014 (formaldehyde \u2192 acrolein) oversimplifies the formose condensation (requires 3 CH2O units with specific aldol/dehydration steps).\",\n            \"approved\": true,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_014\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Add glycolaldehyde as intermediate in rxn_014\", \"Consider mineral catalysts (montmorillonite) for the formose-type condensation\", \"Specify conditions for rxn_003 more carefully\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_003\": 0.70,\n                \"rxn_014\": 0.65,\n                \"rxn_015\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_016\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_019\": 0.85\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.80,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.86,\n            \"environmental_progressio